    <stitle>DT-466E and 530E Diesel Engine Diagnostics Model Years 1999-2000 - ELECTRONIC CONTROL SYSTEM DIAGNOSTICS -
        Circuit Function And Diagnostics - Electronic Pressure Governor
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="troubleshoot" graphiccount="2">
        <title>Electronic Pressure Governor</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Signal Functions</title>
            <figure id="f17503059" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figEG7/EG7315B.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px" box="no"/>
                <caption>Function Diagram for Electronic Pressure Governor</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>The Electronic Pressure Governor (EPG) is an optional feature used for closed loop control of
                hydraulic pressure based on an external hydraulic pressure input and a programmable desired hydraulic
                pressure. This feature is targeted for fluid delivery pumps, especially fire truck applications.
            </para>
            <para>The EPG feature is active when no Electronic Pressure Sensor (EPS) Diagnostic Trouble Code exists, the
                driveline is in its proper state (which is dependent on the type of pump used), the vehicle is
                stationary and its corresponding programmable parameter is turned on.
            </para>
            <para>When the EPG feature is first initiated, the desired hydraulic pressure is ramped up at a programmable
                ramp rate. The limited desired pressure (set point) is then used along with the actual hydraulic
                pressure signal (feedback) to control desired engine speed required to achieve the desired hydraulic
                pressure.
            </para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Fault Detection / Management</title>
            <para>If the ECM detects a an Out of Range High or Low condition in the Electronic Pressure Sensor (EPS)
                circuit, the ECM will set a Diagnostic Trouble Code and disable EPG operation.
            </para>
            <para>The ECM also monitors hydraulic pressure, engine speed and the status of the EPG select switch. If
                pressure loss is detected (also referred to as steady state error) the EPG feature is turned off and a
                corresponding Diagnostic Trouble Code is set.
            </para>
            <figure id="f17503060" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figeg8/eg8759A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="408px" box="no"/>
                <caption>Circuit Diagram for Electronic Pressure Governor</caption>
            </figure>
